answer: @Pilpel: Details are documented: [The WM_PAINT Message](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dd145137.aspx). While this relates to the native window (to which the OpenGL render context is attached), it is usually ignored in code that continuously renders the entire scene. The native window still does get invalidated when obscured portions become visible, or the window is resized, which triggers generation of `WM_PAINT` messages. In your setup the only adverse effect of not validating the invalid region is one superfluous `WM_PAINT` message per frame, that's passed to the message handler.
